Paper “mess” is a chronic condition in our home. This system helps me manage it systematically and easily and lightens the mental load of paper sorting:

1. Every night my kids sort what they want to keep and throw. Already this helps us weed out stuff that is garbage. 
2. Then we display it until our art display is full. This give my kids a sense of pride in what they’ve created and easy access if they want to continue working on something. 
3. After it’s full we move it to our storage basket. This helps my kids feel like I’m not just throwing away their art all the time. Every once in awhile they will remember something they want to look at! 🙈
4. A few times a year when the basket is full I pull out the very best pieces to keep. This makes it easy because it has then sat for long enough that the attachment to most artwork has waned. Also, then I’m only going through the hard work of deciding what to keep or throw a few times a year, rather than every day! 
5. I mark the best ones with their Name/Grade/Year and store it in a folder in their memory bins. This helps me remember the year and keep the artwork straight. I only keep the things they worked really hard on, that shows their progress or that they were most proud of. 

Do you have a system for paper and artwork? I would love to hear about it!

If you’re struggling to homeschool right now:

4️⃣Remember What Season You’re In: This time of year can be prime burnout time. Or maybe you have outside factors creating challenges. Put the blame where it belongs, and not where it doesn’t.

MISSION AND MOTHERHOOD

If you are a mother with a calling on your life it can be hard to hold both mission and motherhood together. 

Your heart may be called to a great work but your hands are full of the other great work of raising and nurturing your children. 

How can we balance both? How can we follow and pursue our passions and godly calling while not shirking the duty and mission of motherhood? 

👥Explain your calling and mission to your children. Talk with them about your passion and why it is so pressed upon your heart!

🧎‍♀️Invite your kids to join in. Pray together, work together, give and serve together. Let them see you on mission and join you!

👩‍👧‍👦Protect your mothering moments. Motherhood is also a mission and calling, so make sure that that there are reserved hours and spaces where you are able to be just “mom”. Keep some mothering moments sacred and not shared. 

📢Ask for help from others. Balance is more of myth than a reality and there will be times where you’re struggling to do two things well. Ask others to help you when you’re struggling and cut back when you need to!

Motherhood and calling don’t have to be opposed to one another (and motherhood might be your main mission right now too and that’s great)!

I know a lot of my fellow CM homeschoolers have been curious about the Living Education Retreat, so here was my biggest take away: 

The entirety of a Charlotte Mason  education rests on her 1st and 20th principles. Only in educating with the Holy Spirit can we truly honor the personhood of each individual child and everything else in a CM education flows from that.

A true education (which really, is merely facilitating self-education), governed by the Holy Spirit, centers on listening to and knowing your child. It is a co-laboring in the pleasure of knowledge of God, man and the universe and its only marks are growth of character.
